<font color="#FF0000">A FEW WORDS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 23 18:58:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Bill Tankerbird,<br>
I've read your posts recently and I had a few comments to make.  First of all, be proud of your service.  There is no more dangerous job as handling dangerous fuel and the planes that haul it.  For what its worth, I've always liked the KC-135 tankers, it must take nerve to handle gallons on fuel.  Fuel keeps the Air Force in the air.  In regards to you feeling bad about your statis or lack of being either a Vietnam vet or even a REMF, I have some things to say.  First, of all, anyone who endures a rocket attack and sees people get killed is a member of the brotherhood of Nam vets.  Forget what a few jerks say to you.  Even someone who serves in the rear has there own moments of terror and hell, with a lifetime of memories.  Just look at the men of the USS Forrestal, that super aircraft carrier.  Those men served in safety off the coast of Nam, but thirty years ago this month, a horrible accident and fire on the ship lead to ordanance explosions, trapped men, hot fires and cruel deaths.  For those sailors, there enemy was fire, not the VC, but their enemy was every bit as bad as the VC.<br><br>
I am a volunteer researcher for vets in helping them get medals, decorations and records from the gov't.  Bill, I think you might have a Vietnam Service medal coming to you. I don't know much about your unit (would like to), but you said you spent 2 days in Nam on a layover and that your unit supported Linebacker 2 planes.  Did you spend ANY TIME in Thailand?<br>
Here are the criteria for eligibilty for the Vietnam Service Medal:<br><br>
A person must meet on of the following to be eligible:<br>
1.  Be attached to or regularly serve for 1 or more days with an organization participating in or directly supporting military operations.<br>
2.  Be attached to or regularly derve for 1 or more days aboard a Naval vessel directly supporting military operations.<br>
3.  Actually participate as a crewmember in one or more aerial flights into airspace above Vietnam and contiguous waters directly supporting military operations.<br>
4.  Serve on temporary duty for 30 consecutive or 60 days nonconsecutive days in Vietnam or contiguous areas, except that time may be waived for personnel participating in actual combat operations.<br>
In addition, support service in Thailand, Cambodia and Laos count as the area of operations covered under the Vietnam service medal.  This info comes from the Dept of Defense Manual of Military Decorations and Awards-August 1985.<br><br>
In addition, everyone who served between 1965 and 1973 had the National Defense Service Medal, which is something to be proud of. I heard that members of the VFW are trying to get the gov't to create a COLD WAR SERVICE MEDAL.  Bill, did you check if your unit received any unit awards.  MANY units received awards and the men could wear the ribbon.  That is a sign of a job well done too.  Just trying to help out.  For what its worth I think of you as Nam vet.  So, welcome home!!<br><br>
Other note:  Despite someone saying I'm not a credible person for not posting my e-mail address here, I still won't.  If you want to e-mail me leave a note here and I can provide my address.  I don't post my e-mail address all over, because my e-mail provider gets screwed up when I get Spam (junk e-mail) and I've learned what devious things people can do with an e-mail address.  It happened to a friend.  If you want to ignore me, well that's too bad, since that defeats the idea of dialog.<br><br>
Hey Ed-You post some very interesting and thought provoking messages.  Keep telling your story and point of view!!!
